('328', '1', '2012-01-04 09:51:53', '2012-01-04 09:51:53', '¬†\r\n\r\nPhuket Water Sports and Activities\r\n\r\nSeakayak, Surfing, Snorkelling, Wakeboard and Sailing\r\n\r\nPhuket Island ‚Äì surrounded by warm tropical waters ‚Äì is a paradise for water sports lovers. The area is well known to scuba enthusiasts but lesser-recognised water activities such a sea kayaking and kite surfing are growing in popularity. Of course, the gentle tides and calm waters from November to April are perfect for snorkeling while the wild and rough waves from May to October are great for surfers. It‚Äôs your call: either gently ride the waves on a cruise or get to your destination ultra quick on a speedboat. Enjoy watersports and activities around Phuket.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nScuba Diving in Phuket\r\n\r\nPhuket rates among the top 10 scuba diving destinations in the world. Spectacular reefs, Unusual underwater rock formations, and huge variety of marine life provide great opportunities for divers at all levels in the Similan Islands,¬†Racha, Koh Phi Phi, Hin Daeng and much more.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nPhuket Sea Kayaking\r\n\r\nSea Kayaking around Phang Nga Bay and Krabi is an amazing experience you really shouldn‚Äôt miss! Discover a unique and hidden world as sturdy canoes weave their way through a network of brilliant crystalline limestone caves, to reveal the mysterious hidden world of the ‚ÄúHongs‚Äù.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSailing in Phuket\r\n\r\nPhuket is one of the premier sailing destinations of Asia. Chartering anything from a small bare-boat through to luxury crewed vessels in the hundred feet range is possible.¬†The Andaman Sea, with Phuket as its hub, will always be Thailand‚Äôs reigning maritime jewel with some of the most beautiful islands and beaches in the region, crystal clear waters and stunning geography.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nCruises in Phuket\r\n\r\nPhang Nga Bay, Phuket and the Phi Phi Islands offer perfect destinations for cruising. Sunset cruises, day sailing or longer cruises on a beautiful Chinese style Junk. Let the crew do the work while you relax, passing through some of the most stunning scenery in Thailand.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSpeedboats in Phuket\r\n\r\nPhi Phi, Phang Nga, Krabi, Similan islands. The great thing about travelling by speedboat, is that you get to see a lot more! Although it‚Äôs slightly more expensive than a normal tour, you get better value for money. You travel in smaller groups, visit places when the crowds have left, and often see places where the main tours don‚Äôt visit.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSurfing in Phuket\r\n\r\nIn case you didn‚Äôt know it, Phuket‚Äôs West Coast is gaining a reputation as a surf destination. Okay, so this is no Waikiki, and surfers here would be the first to admit that, but the island‚Äôs West Coast is the best place for surfing in Thailand.¬†Kata, Karon, Nai Harn, Surin, Kamala and Kalim are the beaches surfers head for. North end of Karon Beach is a top pick for many surfers. East Coast is not the place for surfing, as there is no real waves.\r\n\r\n¬†\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nBeach Sports\r\n\r\n¬†\r\n\r\nCheck out the watersports action off the beach, and find out how to reach the many tiny islands, calm bays and dazzling snorkel sites near Phuket. There‚Äôs lots to see and several ways to see it ‚Äì by yacht, by speedboat, by sea canoe ‚Äì the choice is yours.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nSnorkelling in Phuket\r\n\r\nWith an abundance of colourful marine life, warm waters and easy access, Phuket and its nearby islands are ideal for snorkeling.¬†Swim among parrotfish, clownfish, needlefish, damselfish and surgeonfish, and you may even spot an octopus or two peeking out from under a rock\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nKite Surfing in Phuket\r\n\r\nKitesurfing is one of the fastest growing sports in Phuket. Beginners appreciate the shallow waters and gentle breezes of the southeast coast while over at Nai Yang and Layan beaches in northwest Phuket, more practiced kitesurfers really let rip with acrobatic stunts.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nJet Skis in Phuket\r\n\r\nJet-skiing is for many the best way to have water sports‚Äô fun while on holiday. Those who love to make their own waves can head to Phuket‚Äôs main beaches where the machines are for hire. But do so at your own risk. There exist insurance in Thailand that will cover jet ski rental, however it will only cover minimal amounts. Many of the stalls that offer jet skis for hire, will try and rob you of your money. ( Damage caused will be much more expensive than what insurance covers + lost income in the 10 days it will take to get parts etc etc ) Google jet ski mafia or jet ski scams and you know what I am talking about. Latest scam involves them taking photos of the jet ski and you then assume the scratches and bumps are in the photo and you feel safe. Well that‚Äôs a false sense of safe, as the photos will be edited very quickly at a shop nearby, so the jet ski will look new, without bumps and scratches in the photo upon your return. If you still want to go, take your own photos of the jet ski and take a lot of photos. If the rental guys won‚Äôt let you take photos, you know what type they are. A new jet ski costs around 500.000 ‚Äì 700.000 baht depending on make and model. But really just stay away.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nFishing in Phuket\r\n\r\nGame fishing in Phuket is an exciting, year-round activity. The Andaman Sea has an abundance of deep sea fighting fish including dorado, tuna, sailfish and marlin, while sea bass, barracuda, giant trevally, queenfish and mangrove jack are found closer to shore.\r\n\r\n¬†\r\n\r\n¬†\r\n\r\n¬†', '', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', '328', '', '', '2012-01-27 10:49:59', '2012-01-27 10:49:59', '', '0', 'http://www.genesisvilla.com/?p=328', '17', 'nav_menu_item', '', '0'),
('329', '1', '2012-01-04 10:09:09', '2012-01-04 10:09:09', '&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Discover Thai Cuisine in Phuket</strong>\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-334\" title=\"thai breakfast\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/thai-breakfast.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\nMany foreigners know something about Thai food from going to Thai restaurants in their home countries. Others have never tried it but have heard of its reputation for gorgeous if mouth-searing tastes - and plan to give it a try while in Phuket.\r\n\r\nSome Thai dishes are, shall we say, an acquired taste, so here Phuket.com offers some guidelines for the Thai cuisine beginner, which we hope will give you an enjoyable and tasty start.\r\n\r\n<strong>Thai Breakfast</strong>\r\n\r\nOutside Bangkok, Phuket probably has the widest variety of food choices in Thailand. One of the main reasons for this is the island‚Äôs long history as an international place, going back to the tin-mining boom of more than a century ago. These days, the island‚Äôs inhabitants come from all corners of the globe, but varieties of Thai cuisine are still very much the favorite food. Let‚Äôs start the day right with breakfast.\r\n\r\n<strong>Kao Tom</strong> is boiled rice served with a choice of meat and other titbits and sometimes also an egg. Healthy and not too heavy, it is one of the most popular dishes for Thais at the start of the day. However, if kao tom seems a bit basic, then Phuket has plenty more to offer, such as:\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-332\" title=\"oeuf\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/oeuf.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Roti &amp; Mussaman Curry</strong> is influenced by the cuisines of Malaysia and the Indian Subcontinent. There are two elements: roti, which is Indian-style unleaven bread, and a small bowl of curry made with your choice of beef, chicken or lamb. You usually also get a fried egg with it. The set with a drink will cost around 50 baht (less than two Euro). The restaurant best-known in Phuket for this dish is Roti Chaofa, on Chao Fa Rd in Phuket City, next to the Siam Commercial Bank. This family-run place has been in the business more than 30 years, serving up a secret-recipe curry passed down through the generations. The shop opens daily from 0600 to noon. Tel: 66 (0) 76 221771.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-330\" title=\"Dim sum\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Dim-sum.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Dim sum</strong>, which has its roots firmly in Chinese cuisine, is probably the most fun you can have at breakfast; a sort of Chinese tapas. Dim sum restaurants serve a huge variety of different dishes, all in small portions - enough usually for a couple of bites - all delivered in small bamboo containers, though some restaurants serve the food in small bowls instead. Many of the dishes have pork as the main ingredient. If it‚Äôs your first time for dim sum, try The Metropole hotel in Phuket City, which has dim-sum a la carte for 32 Baht a serving or, for groups of three or four people, a set menu for 500 baht. Opening hours are 1100 to 1400. Tel: 66 (0) 76 214020.\r\n\r\n<strong>Kanom Jeen</strong> is a common dish all over Thailand, with huge variations, but all based on kanom jeen, or soft rice noodles. It‚Äôs served with a choice of curries and almost always comes with a side dish heaped with fresh and boiled vegetables. Many people will also add a boiled egg. Phuket is unusual in that you can get kanom jeen as early as 0500; most Thais do not usually eat kanom jeen for breakfast. One serving will cost you 10 to 20 baht, including the vegetables. There‚Äôs a kanom jeen shop on almost every street corner in Phuket. Just look for the one that draws the biggest crowds.\r\n\r\n<strong>Thai Lunch</strong>\r\n\r\nFor lunch in Phuket, forget burgers, sandwiches and chicken nuggets; Thailand has food that arrives just as fast but is much fresher and tastier.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-337\" title=\"Thai Lunch 1\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Thai-Lunch-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\nIt has to be admitted that there is a serious problem that even Thai office workers on lunch break face: the choice is enormous. Where to go? What to eat? Here are some popular suggestions: <strong>Kway Tio</strong> (noodle soup), <strong>Pad Thai Goong</strong> (Thai fried rice noodles with prawns), <strong>Pad Kapow Neua</strong> (stir-fried basil with beef), <strong>Pad See Iew</strong> (noodles in soy sauce) and <strong>Kao Pad</strong> (fried rice with a choice of meat or seafood).\r\n\r\nAll of these dishes are cooked fresh right after you order; each takes about 3-5 minutes. The price for a lunch, including a drink, is always less than two Euro.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-338\" title=\"Thai Lunch 2\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Thai-Lunch-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\nOne other ‚Äúmust try‚Äù while you‚Äôre in Phuket is <strong>Kao Niow with Gai Yang</strong> (sticky rice with barbecued chicken). Some restaurants, especially those set up by people from the northeast of Thailand, specialise in this dish, which is best eaten without benefit of cutlery - a guarantee of informality.\r\n\r\nMany people never encounter sticky rice before coming to Thailand so at first try you‚Äôll probably end up with bits of rice stuck to your fingers, wrists, your elbows, all over. Definitely fun, and thoroughly delicious.\r\n\r\n<strong>Thai Dinner</strong>\r\n\r\nThais have no hard and fast rules about what to eat for dinner. Many Thais will simply have a light, healthy bowl of noodles. But for families, dinner is the main meal of the day, the one time they are all likely to come together, so the meal may be more elaborate, with dishes that take longer to prepare.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-335\" title=\"Thai Dinner 1\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Thai-Dinner-1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\nFor families or groups of friends, dinner never consists of a single dish. There is always a variety in the centre of the table for everyone to share - a fine way to bring everyone together.\r\n\r\nIf you are ordering dinner for a group, we suggest you choose a balance of dishes: something that‚Äôs spicy balanced by something that‚Äôs not; a vegetable dish to balance a meat dish. You should also include in your order either a clear soup or a curry, or both. To help you choose, here are three sample Thai dinner ‚Äúsets‚Äù for 3-5 people.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-336\" title=\"Thai Dinner 2\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Thai-Dinner-2.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\n<strong>Set A</strong>: Satay Gai (chicken marinated in herbs and honey then grilled, served with peanut sauce); Pad Pak Ruam (mixed fried vegetables); and Tom Yam Goong (spicy-sour soup with prawns).\r\n\r\n<strong>Set B</strong>: Yum Pla Dook Foo (spicy salad with fried catfish); Penang Neua (red beef curry); and Gaeng Jeud Moo Taohu (mild clear soup with pork and tofu).\r\n\r\n<strong>Set C</strong>: Pad Priew Waan Pak (sweet and savoury fried vegetables); Laab Gai (spicy minced chicken salad); and Tom Kah Talay (Coconut milk soup with seafood, flavoured with galangal).\r\n\r\n<strong>Table Manners</strong>\r\n\r\nSince Thai food is prepared in bite-size morsels, it‚Äôs very rare to see a knife used at a Thai table; normally it‚Äôs spoon in the right hand, fork in the left. In politer society, each dish will arrive with its own serving spoon, so don‚Äôt use your own spoon to dig into a dish of food in the middle of the table. Each person will have his or her own plate of rice. Use the serving spoon to take a small amount of food from one of the dishes and eat that before trying something else - it‚Äôs not considered very polite to heap your plate. Besides, you‚Äôll enjoy the food much more if you take it one taste at a time, instead of mixing all the flavours together.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-333\" title=\"Table Manners\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/Table-Manners.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\nA clean plate is a good thing in Thai society - it shows you think your host or cook has served up a delicious meal. While food in the bowls in the centre can often be kept in the fridge for the next day, food on individual plates cannot, and many Thais consider that a sad waste in a world where many people are still starving. So finish what‚Äôs on your plate.\r\n\r\n<strong>How to Choose a Thai Restaurant </strong>\r\n\r\nOne of the best places to find a good Thai restaurant in Phuket is along its West Coast since most restaurants there have menus in English. Such places are in Patong, Kata and Karon. Many of these restaurants also provide ‚Äòphoto menus‚Äô and this simplifies things for the rookie Thai food diner. However West Coast restaurants are usually pricier than their East Coast counterparts. In Phuket Town, Chalong and Rawai areas always very reasonable prices.\r\n\r\n<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-331\" title=\"How to Choose a Thai Restaurant\" src=\"http://www.genesisvilla.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/01/How-to-Choose-a-Thai-Restaurant-.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"250\" height=\"166\" />\r\n\r\nKan Eang Sea Food Restaurant, Chalong.\r\n\r\nOf course, it‚Äôs always easier if the wait staff speak English so you can make it clear just how spicy you‚Äôd like that curry and whether you‚Äôd prefer chicken, beef or fish.\r\n\r\nCleanliness is more important than fancy d√©cor. You‚Äôd be surprised at how many simple and basic-looking restaurants in Thailand actually serve fantastic food. And you can bet your bottom dollar that they keep their place meticulously clean. And follow the crowds; it‚Äôs always a good sign if a restaurant is crowded ‚Äì a well-frequented restaurant is bound to deliver the goods.\r\n<h4></h4>\r\n<h4></h4>\r\n<h4>Tips</h4>\r\n<h4>Don‚Äôt be scared off by the word ‚Äúspicy‚Äù. As with anything else, there are degrees of spiciness. Depending on your preference, you can order any dish to be cooked just a little bit spicy, medium, or blazing hot.</h4>\r\nNo matter what your local friends may say, avoid local food carts or food stands. If this is your first time eating Thai food, it‚Äôs best to ensure that you get food that not only tastes and smells good but is also hygienically prepared.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'First time thai food', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'first-time-thai-food', '', '', '2012-01-05 11:50:27', '2012-01-05 11:50:27', '', '0', 'http://www.genesisvilla.com/?page_id=329', '0', 'page', '', '0'),
